#1 Permanent atrial fibrillation with severe atrial enlargement
#2 Systemic hypertension
#3 Coronary artery disease, status-post surgical revascularization
#4 Peripheral arterial disease with claudication
#5 Patent foreman ovale
#6 Severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease
#7 Chronic kidney disease (stage III)
#8 Cecal adenocarcinoma, status-post right hemicolectomy
Mr. Burks has demonstrated intermittent increases in his heart rate and blood pressure following surgery.  We discussed potential mechanisms of worsening ventricular rate control with atrial fibrillation as well as elevated blood pressures in the postoperative setting and specifically potential implications of his surgery with respect to medication absorption.  He is currently without any symptomatic cardiopulmonary complaints.
SPECIFIC RECOMMENDATIONS
1.  Obtain 12-lead electrocardiogram.
2.  Continue diltiazem 60-mg four times daily in lieu of long-acting diltiazem.
3.  Increase Losartan to 25-mg daily.
4.  Update electrolytes and creatinine; creatinine will need to be followed given increase in ARB.
5.  Continue monitoring heart rate and blood pressure.
6.  If Mr. Burks is to remain in the area following hospital dismissal, a 24-hour Holter monitor and six-hour ambulatory blood pressure can be performed with a follow-up in Dr. Vinny Salzer's outpatient clinic.
7.  Should the patient be dismissed and return home without cardiology follow-up here, he should be seen within one-week by either his primary-care physician or a local cardiologist to review hemodynamics.
8.  Coumadin has been reinitiated; the use of aspirin 81-mg daily needs to be discussed on an outpatient basis given Mr. Burks's coronary artery disease.
Discussed in detail with the patient and his son, and I believe all questions were answered.  The above recommendations were discussed with Dr. Salzer.  Please contact the Cardiology Service if his heart rate and blood pressure remain elevated or if we can be of further assistance prior to Mr. Burks's dismissal.
Addendum:  ECG reviewed. Increase diltiazem to 90 mg four times daily if heart rate remains elevated (only one dose of diltiazem administered today prior to the ECG).

