[start section id="20102"]

Atrial fibrillation and hypertension.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Burks is an 83-year-old male with longstanding permanent atrial fibrillation; coronary artery disease, status-post surgical revascularization; peripheral arterial disease with lower-extremity claudication; multiple cardiovascular risk factors (systemic hypertension and dyslipidemia); severe obstructive pulmonary disease with emphysema; and recently-diagnosed adenocarcinoma of the cecum.  Mr. Burks underwent open right hemicolectomy and ileotransverse colostomy on October 14, 2010.  He has done reasonably well following surgery.  He is complaining of intermittent hiccups and difficulty having a bowel movement.  Due to an elevated heart rate and blood pressure, the Cardiology Service was asked to provide additional recommendations.
Mr. Burks denies any chest discomfort, dyspnea, orthopnea, paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea, peripheral edema, lightheadedness, palpitations, or syncope.  He reports monitoring his blood pressure at-home on a frequent basis (three times daily).  His morning systolic blood pressure typically exceeds 160 mm Hg and averages between 120 to 130 mm Hg throughout the remainder of the day.  He reports his resting heart rate at-home is around 90 beats per minute.  His recorded heart rates over the past several days are typically between 90 and 100 beats per minute.  Over the past 36 hours, he has recorded heart rates of up to 120 beats per minute.  His systolic blood pressure has consistently been greater than 140 mm Hg and earlier this morning was 168 mm Hg.  He has undergone several modifications to his cardiovascular medical regimen as an outpatient in the weeks leading up to surgery.  Beta-blocker therapy was discontinued in favor of a calcium-channel blocker given his significant obstructive pulmonary disease and response to bronchodilators.  Digoxin was discontinued given his preserved left ventricular ejection fraction and the absence of heart failure.  Diuretics were modified and the angiotensin receptor blocker dose reduced.

[end section id="20103"]

